cter are listed under alternate advancement from your inventory screen.  They are divided into 3 categories: General, Archetype, and Class. At lvl 51, you are allowed to direct some (or all) of your normally earned experience into an alternate experience pool that is expressed by a second experience bar. This bar looks and behaves the same way as the normal experience bar except when it is full you gain one spendable experience point rather than gaining a level. Experience points can be saved and spent whenever and however you wish so long as and prerequisites for the skill you wish to train in have been met.  In the begging you can only spend points in General, which is the same for every class.  In General, you can increase your base runspeed, regeneration rate, and increase any of your base stats and resists (str, agi, dex, FR, MR, etc...). You will gain the title of Baron / Baroness when you spend 6 points here. Once you spend 6 points in General and have attained lvl 55, you can start spending points in Archytype area if you wish. Archytype abilities cost 2 points each to train and give you some really nice abilities that are different for melees and casters. Melees, for example, can gain the ability to finish mobs in one hit if it is under 10percent and wanting to run. Melees can also train in abilities that allow them to take up to 10 percent less melee damage  per hit, aviod 10 percent more melee attacks and either gain the ability to critical hit with a weapon or increase their chances of landing one if they have the skill already. Casters also have some great archytypes but I can't think of them right now. I know wizzys have an ability that allows them to increase their possiblility of landing a critical blast. Once you spend 12 points in archytypes (6 trainings) you gain your next title which will either be Veteran, Venerable, Sir/Lady, or something else depending on class. After you spend 12 points in Archetype and have attained lvl 59, you can spend points in the Class area. This is where the really good stuff is =)  In Class, every class has it's own unique ablilities and some are insane... Warriors, for example, can gain the skill to flurry (additional 2 attacks from primary, so 6 possible weapon attacks possible per round), can significantly improve their dual wield roll percentage, gain the ability to taunt everything within a small radius, and the ability to make the entire party immune to fear for a time, and double reposte. Spend enough points here you get your final title which varies from class to class. I know warriors become Marshals, Monks become Sensi, but I can't remember the others.<br><br>As per difficulty I would say AA points are easier than lvl 51xp but harder than 50xp so somewhere in between. This may have all changed now with the supposed death of hell levels. Also, when you die you will always lose xp from your main xp pool, not your alt avancement pool. Once you earn AA xp and points they can never be lost.<br><br>Hope that answers a few of your questions =)<br><br>Baron Karidan Ravenclaw<br>Champion of the 54th season <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#7c96b9><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub88.ezboard.com/utwick.showPublicProfile?language=EN>twick</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Polar Bear Cub</span><br>  Posts: 213<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/7/02 5:06:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub88.ezboard.com/fepicheroes73161frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=459.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: AA...... How does it work?</span><hr size=1> Thx Kar <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Another question.... The exp u gain in the exp pool is exactly the same as the one